{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180920210915|860467368","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Keith_Rothfus","to":"Keith Rothfus"}],"pages":{"35854195":{"pageid":35854195,"ns":0,"title":"Keith Rothfus","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-20T21:25:09Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Keith Rothfus\n|image       = Keith Rothfus.png\n|state       = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district    = {{ushr|PA|12|12th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Mark Critz]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Keith James Rothfus\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1962|4|25}}\n|birth_place = [[Endicott, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]\n|spouse      = Elsie Rothfus\n|children    = 6\n|education   = [[Buffalo State College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Notre Dame]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|rothfus.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Keith James Rothfus''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|\u0252|\u03b8|f|\u0259|s}} (born April 25, 1962)<ref name=bio>{{cite web |title=Keith James Rothfus|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/keith-james-rothfus-60544|publisher=The Washington Times |accessdate=November 8, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110180313/http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/keith-james-rothfus-60544 |archivedate=January 10, 2013}}</ref> is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district]]. He succeeded [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Mark Critz]], whom he defeated in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2012|2012 election]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Cernetich|first=Kelly|title=Critz Concedes Race to Rothfus |url=http://www.politicspa.com/critz-concedes-race-to-rothfus/44075|publisher=PoliticsPA |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rothfus wins seat in Pa.'s redrawn 12th Congressional District|url=http://www.wpxi.com/news/news/rothfus-wins-seat-pas-redrawn-12th-congressional-d/nSy5k|publisher=WPXI|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> Prior to serving in Congress, he worked as an attorney. After new congressional district maps were released by the Pennsylvania Supreme Court in February 2018, Rothfus became a candidate in [[Pennsylvania's 17th congressional district]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRothfus was born in 1962 in [[Endicott, New York]]. He graduated from [[West Seneca West Senior High School]] in 1980. He graduated from the [[State University of New York College at Buffalo]] with a bachelor's degree in [[information systems]]. He later earned his Juris Doctor from the [[University of Notre Dame Law School]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/Keith_Rothfus|title=Keith Rothfus|publisher=Ballotpedia |accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Law career==\nFor most of his adult life, Rothfus has been a corporate attorney. He was employed by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] from 2006 to 2007. He has also been a member of the [[Edgeworth, Pennsylvania]] [[Zoning in the United States|zoning board]]. He serves on the board of directors of the Veterans Leadership Program of Western Pennsylvania.<ref name=bio/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://keithrothfus.com/who-is-keith-rothfus|title=The Keith You Know |publisher=keithrothfus.com|accessdate=November 18, 2012|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019154614/http://keithrothfus.com/who-is-keith-rothfus |archivedate=October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Keith Rothfus, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg|thumb|Rothfus' first Congressional portrait]]\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010#District 4}}\n\nRothfus decided to run for Congress in [[Pennsylvania's 4th congressional district]]. In the Republican primary, he defeated U.S. Attorney [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] 65%\u201335%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=494772|title=PA \u2013 District 04 \u2013 R Primary Race|date=May 18, 2010|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> Rothfus challenged Democrat U.S. Congressman [[Jason Altmire]], losing 51%\u201349%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=493126|title=PA \u2013 District 04 Race |date=November 2, 2010|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref><ref name=bio1>{{cite news|last=Schmitz|first=Jon and McNulty, Timothy|title=Rothfus upsets Critz in bitter battle for U.S. House|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/news/politics-state/rothfus-upsets-critz-in-bitter-battle-660971|accessdate=November 8, 2012|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012#District 12}}\n\nAfter redistricting, most of the 4th District was merged with the [[Johnstown, Pennsylvania|Johnstown]]-based [[Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district]]. Rothfus won the Republican primary unopposed. In the general election, he faced incumbent Democrat [[Mark Critz]], who had defeated incumbent Jason Altmire in the Democratic primary. Rothfus led Critz in fundraising for the second half of 2012. It was a highly competitive election, with outside groups spending nearly $10 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njherald.com/story/20022902/w-pa-house-race-seen-as-a-key-congressional-race|title=New Jersey Herald \u2013 GOP's Rothfus beats incumbent Critz in W. Pa. race|publisher=Njherald.com|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRothfus defeated Critz 52%\u201348%.<ref name=bio1/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=53&OfficeID=11|title=Commonwealth of PA \u2013 Elections Information|publisher=Electionreturns.state.pa.us|date=November 6, 2012|accessdate=November 18, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116114702/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=53&OfficeID=11|archivedate=November 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/PA |title=2012 Election Results Map by State \u2013 Live Voting Updates|publisher=Politico.com |accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> He took office when the [[113th United States Congress|113th Congress]] convened on January 3, 2013.\n\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2014#District 12}}\n\nRothfus sought a second term in the U.S. House in 2014. He was re-nominated in the May 20 Republican primary and faced Democratic nominee Erin McClelland in the general election. He defeated McClelland 59%\u201341%, winning a second term.<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Pennsylvania House Election Results|url=http://www.politico.com/2014-election/results/map/house/pennsylvania/#.VFoQZPnF9qU|publisher=Politico|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n;2018\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2018#District 17}}\n\nFor his first three terms, Rothfus represented a district stretching from the northwestern suburbs of Pittsburgh to [[Johnstown, Pennsylvania|Johnstown]]. After the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] threw out the old congressional map as unconstitutional and replaced it with a map of its own, Rotfhus' district was renumbered as the [[Pennsylvania's 17th congressional district|17th District]] and reconfigured as a more compact district in the northern and western suburbs of Pittsburgh. Democrat [[Conor Lamb]], who won [[Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district special election, 2018|a special election]] for the neighboring [[Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district|18th District]], had his home drawn into the new 17th and filed to run for a full term there on March 20.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/03/20/conor-lamb-won-pennsylvanias-18th-district-tuesday-he-filed-states-17th-district/443460002/|title=Conor Lamb won Pennsylvania's 18th district. Tuesday he filed in the state's 17th District|author1=Eliza Collins |publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> On paper, the new 17th is far less Republican than its predecessor; Trump carried the old 12 by 20 points, but would have carried the new 17th by just 2.5 points.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prose|first1=J.D.|title=U.S. Rep.-elect Conor Lamb in primary race to challenge Rep. Keith Rothfus|url=http://www.timesonline.com/news/20180314/us-rep-elect-conor-lamb-in-primary-race-to-challenge-rep-keith-rothfus|accessdate=March 26, 2018 |publisher=The Times|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit|Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [https://judiciary.house.gov/press-release/chairman-goodlatte-welcomes-rothfus-to-the-house-judiciary-committee/ United States House Judiciary Committee]\n\n==Political positions==\nRothfus is a [[Conservatism|conservative]] and member of the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|title=Member List|publisher=Republican Study Committee|format=|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Human trafficking ===\nAlong with Congressman [[Juan Vargas]] (D-CA), Rothfus introduced the \"Fight Illicit Networks and Detect Trafficking Act\" (or the FIND Trafficking Act), H.R. 6069. On July 17, 2018, the House passed the S.488, the JOBS and Investor Confidence Act of 2018, which contained the text of the FIND Trafficking Act. The FIND Trafficking Act directs the [[Office of the Comptroller of the Currency|Comptroller of the Currency]] to study how virtual currencies can facilitate human trafficking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rothfus.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rothfus-supports-economic-growth-package-includes-his-bipartisan-anti|title=Rothfus Supports Economic Growth Package that Includes his Bipartisan Anti-Drug and Human Trafficking Bill|date=2018-07-17|work=Congressman Keith Rothfus|access-date=2018-09-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Finance ===\nOn July 20, 2017, Rothfus introduced H.J.Res.111, which nullifies a rule submitted by the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]].<ref>https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-joint-resolution/111</ref>\n\n=== Gay rights ===\nIn 2015, he signed onto a resolution which would amend the U.S. Constitution so that only marriages between men and women are legal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=GOP resolution proposes gay marriage ban |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/233257-gop-resolution-proposes-gay-marriage-ban |accessdate=March 26, 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Rothfus has a 0 rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]], an LGBT rights advocacy group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollcall.com/politics/republicans-dont-mention-lgbt-community-target-orlando-shooting|title=Republicans Who Didn't Say 'LGBT' in Their Orlando Statements|author=Andrew Breiner|website=Roll Call|publisher=Roll Call|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nIn early 2017, efforts were made to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act. Approximately 130 of Rothfus's constituents requested a town hall to discuss their concerns about removed/reduced health coverage. Frustrated citizens sponsored and invited Rothfus to a town hall; he declined.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Congressman Keith Rothfus dodges 130 constituents in first week back in district|url=http://www.pghcitypaper.com/PolitiCrap/archives/2017/02/22/us-congressman-keith-rothfus-dodges-130-constituents-in-first-week-back-in-district|website=Pittsburgh City Paper |publisher=Pittsburgh City Paper|author=Ryan Deto|date=February 22, 2017}}</ref> Some of Rothfus's constituents reportedly started a PAC to motivate him to meet with them.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Yinzers Against Jagoffs' PAC forms demanding more accessibility from U.S. Rep. Keith Rothfus |url=http://www.pghcitypaper.com/PolitiCrap/archives/2017/03/20/yinzers-against-jagoffs-pac-forms-demanding-more-accessibility-from-us-rep-keith-rothfus|website=Pittsburgh City Paper |publisher=Ryan Deto|date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> On June 3, activists and constituents purportedly frustrated with Rothfus's refusal to host a town hall interrupted a Chamber of Commerce meeting that Rothfus was attending.<ref>{{cite web|author=Emily Balser|title=Protesters interrupt Rothfus meeting|url=http://triblive.com/local/valleynewsdispatch/12365618-74/protesters-interrupt-rothfus-meeting|website=TribLive|publisher=Trib Total Media|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Insurance regulation ===\nOn September 12, 2018, a bill that Rothfus had introduced, the State Insurance Regulation Preservation Act (H.R. 5059), passed in the U.S. House of Representatives. The legislation would tailor the supervision of the [[Federal Reserve System|Federal Reserve]] over [[Holding company|holding companies]] that own [[Savings and loan association|thrifts]] (savings and loans banks). The bill streamlines regulator's approach to insurance savings and loan holding companies (ISLHCs) by enacting several reforms.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rothfus.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/house-passes-rothfus-bipartisan-bill-tailor-supervision-insurance|title=House Passes Rothfus\u2019 Bipartisan Bill to Tailor the Supervision of Insurance-Focused Savings and Loan Holding Companies|date=2018-09-13|work=Congressman Keith Rothfus|access-date=2018-09-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Natural disasters ===\nIn 2013, Rothfus voted against a bill to provide disaster relief funding to victims of [[Hurricane Sandy]]. Referring to the bill's funding offsets for the [[National Flood Insurance Program]], he said it was \"irresponsible to raise an insolvent program's debt ceiling without making reforms.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/pennsylvania/sewickley/rothfus-votes-against-hurricane-sandy-relief-package|title=Rothfus Votes Against Hurricane Sandy Relief|author=Larissa Dudkiewicz|website=Patch|publisher=Patch|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref> \n\n=== Refugees ===\nIn January 2017, Rothfus issued a statement in support of [[Executive Order 13769|President Trump's executive order on refugees]].<ref>{{cite web|date=January 30, 2017|title=Rothfus statement on President Trump's executive order on refugees|url=http://www.wearecentralpa.com/news/rothfus-statement-on-president-trumps-executive-order-on-refugees/647166147|website=WeAreCentralPa.com |publisher=Kevin Valentine|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Rothfus voted to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act,<ref>{{cite news|date=May 4, 2017|title=How Every Member Voted on the House Health Care Bill |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/04/us/politics/house-vote-republican-health-care-bill.html|website=New York Times|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The American Health Care Act Makes Unsustainable Cuts to Medicaid|url=http://blog.aarp.org/2017/05/03/the-american-health-care-act-makes-unsustainable-cuts-to-medicaid|website=AARP|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=This is what Americans will really dislike about the House 'Trumpcare' bill|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/05/05/this-is-what-americans-will-really-dislike-about-the-house-trumpcare-bill|website=CNN|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref> including provisions to defund Planned Parenthood.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sandhya Somashekhar |first1=Paige W. Cunningham|title=Congressional health-care bill 'defunds' Planned Parenthood |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/congressional-health-care-bill-defunds-planned-parenthood/2017/05/04/afdc3b5a-30f1-11e7-8674-437ddb6e813e_story.html|website=Washington Post |publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=May 5, 2017}}</ref> The bill included an exemption for Congress that was later removed,<ref>{{cite news|author=Linda Qiu|title=Fact Check: Is Congress Exempt From the G.O.P. Health Bill?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/04/us/politics/fact-check-congress-exemption-republican-health-bill.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref> and the MacArthur amendment, which allowed states to opt out of covering preexisting conditions.<ref>{{cite web|title=The GOP's big lie: Healthcare bill 'protects people with preexisting conditions'|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/lazarus/la-fi-lazarus-gop-healthcare-macarthur-amendment-20170504-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 5, 2017}}</ref> \n\nRothfus is supported by [[America First Policies]], a PAC that runs pro-Rothfus ads.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Daily 202: What does Trump have to hide? Secretive White House unapologetic about clawing back transparency |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/daily-202/2017/04/17/daily-202-what-does-trump-have-to-hide-secretive-white-house-unapologetic-about-clawing-back-transparency/58f411b3e9b69b3a72331e8e|website=The Washington Post|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRothfus resides with his wife, Elsie, and their six children in [[Sewickley, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=bio/> He is a survivor of appendix cancer.\n\nHe and his family attend St. James Roman Catholic Church in [[Sewickley, Pennsylvania|Sewickley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=229771|title=Our Campaigns - Candidate - Keith Rothfus|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Keith Rothfus}}\n* [http://rothfus.house.gov/ Congressman Keith Rothfus] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.keithrothfus.com Keith Rothfus for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Keith_Rothfus_%5BR-12%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|keithrothfus}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state = Pennsylvania\n| district = 12\n| before = [[Mark Critz]]\n| years = 2013\u2013present\n| after = }}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Rice]]<br>R-[[South Carolina]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=289th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Raul Ruiz (politician)|Raul Ruiz]]<br>D-[[California]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{PA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 113th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Pennsylvania]]}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/113}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/114}}\n{{USCongRep/PA/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rothfus, Keith}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:State University of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Edgeworth, Pennsylvania]]\n[